{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524506"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:05:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:05:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14002"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14002"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.59,0.04,0.02,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98099"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6651"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14002"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80605"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33639"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98099"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of vague upper abdominal pain. She reports anorexia and a change in her bowel habits. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Blood tests reveal iron deficiency anaemia. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gallbladder malignancy","Transverse colon cancer","Renal cell carcinoma","Psoas abscess","Pancreatic cancer"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and imaging findings in this case are most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Etransverse colon cancer\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s symptoms of vague upper abdominal pain, anorexia, and change in bowel habits are typical of colon cancer. The presence of iron deficiency anaemia is also a common finding in right-sided colon cancers due to chronic, occult blood loss. The CT image shows a mass in the transverse colon, which corresponds with these clinical findings. The arrow points to the tumour (Image). Some dilated colon can be seen immediately proximal to the stenosing tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E: There is likely a small cyst in the kidney seen on scan but it doesn\u0027t appear concerning from this image and would not explain the clinical scenario\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epsoas abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with fever, back pain, and potentially a limp. The CT appearance would show a fluid collection rather than a solid mass, and the clinical presentation does not fit this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallbladder malignancy\u003C/strong\u003E often presents with right upper quadrant pain and jaundice. While it can cause vague abdominal symptoms, the location of the mass in the image is not consistent with a gallbladder origin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic cancer\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with more severe abdominal pain, often radiating to the back, along with weight loss and jaundice. The location of the mass in the image is not consistent with a pancreatic origin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of vague upper abdominal pain, change in bowel habits, iron deficiency anaemia, and the CT findings of a mass in the transverse colon are most consistent with a transverse colon cancer. This diagnosis explains all the clinical features and imaging findings presented in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transverse colon tumours can present with vague upper abdominal pain and iron deficiency anaemia.","CT imaging is crucial for diagnosing and staging colonic tumours.","Changes in bowel habits and anorexia are common symptoms of colon cancer."],"references":["Duan B, Zhao Y, Bai J, et al. Colorectal Cancer: An Overview. In: Morgado-Diaz JA, editor. Gastrointestinal Cancers. Brisbane (AU): Exon Publications; 2022 Sep 30. Chapter 1. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK586003/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80605"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14002"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20913"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21811"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20913"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vxvmsc6h373PqXVJTRzZiRfHn7iHGw.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vxvmsc6h373PqXVJTRzZiRfHn7iHGw.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":501,"height":701}},{"type":"media","id":"21811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21811"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7oXZbmOaaBQTtTclFLzyjYnt91Wq1Q.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7oXZbmOaaBQTtTclFLzyjYnt91Wq1Q.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":501,"height":701}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"8060